Date: 0/0/1962
Source: Australian & NZ English [TS]
Author: SYDER & HODGETTS
Vol / Page: 198
Edition: 1974
Quote: To crash heavily either physically, or, in one's expectations. .in 4;`As he ran tripped over a root, and come a gutser on the stones - he was half-stunned when he got up.' `The shop, stock andbooks were all in order, but there was no business, no customers; he said he came a gutser on that deal.'
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1925
Source: Soldier and Sailor Words
Author: FRASER & GIBBONS
Vol / Page: 113
Edition:
Quote: GUTZER, TO COME A: To `crash' or fall badly. (Originally an Air Force term with reference to an aeroplane.) Also used generally.  To get into serious trouble, e.g., `He's before a court martial and looks like coming a gutzer'. `Gutzer' is pre-war slang, and an old term among Scottish boys for falling flat on the water in diving, instead of making a clean header.
Notes:

